sec.p:
To evaluate response time consistency for humans and monkeys, we collated the response times across all participants and calculated the average response time between randomly dividing into two equal groups. For each search pair, outliers more than 3 scaled median absolute deviations from the median were removed for each search pair. Doing so improved the response consistency overall for both humans and monkeys. We confirmed that all results were qualitatively similar even without this step. We then calculated the response consistency as the split-half correlation as the average Pearson’s correlation coefficient between 1000 random splits (rsh, with repeated sampling). The statistical significance of this correlation (psh) was determined as follows:


psh=1−number of significant(p<0.05)split−half correlations total number of random splits 
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle p_{s h}=1-\frac{\text { number of significant }(p<0.05) \text { split }- \text { half correlations }}{\text { total number of random splits }}$$\end{document}

To compare inter-individual differences across humans and monkeys, we calculated the correlation distance between every pair of participants as follows:


ri,j=r(di,dj)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle r_{i, j}=r\left(d_{i}, d_{j}\right)$$\end{document}

In order to compare psychometric curves, we fit a sigmoid by scaling and shifting the normal cumulative distribution function (CDF, ‘normcdf’ in MATLAB) as follows:


p=A∗F(x∣μ,σ)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle p=A * F(x \mid \mu, \sigma)$$\end{document}
